      <h2>Understanding Your Closing Costs</h2>

      <p>Closing costs in Utah typically range from <strong>2-5% of the purchase price</strong> for buyers. Here's a breakdown of common costs:</p>

      <h3>Buyer's Typical Costs:</h3>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Lender's title insurance</strong> ‚Äî Protects your mortgage company</li>
        <li><strong>Loan origination fees</strong> ‚Äî Charged by your lender</li>
        <li><strong>Appraisal fee</strong> ‚Äî Usually $400-600</li>
        <li><strong>Home inspection</strong> ‚Äî Usually $300-500 (paid before closing)</li>
        <li><strong>Recording fees</strong> ‚Äî County charges to record the deed and mortgage</li>
        <li><strong>Prepaid items</strong> ‚Äî Property taxes, homeowner's insurance, and mortgage interest prorated to closing</li>
        <li><strong>Escrow reserves</strong> ‚Äî Initial deposits for your tax and insurance escrow account</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Seller's Typical Costs:</h3>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Owner's title insurance policy</strong> ‚Äî Customarily paid by the seller in Utah</li>
        <li><strong>Real estate agent commissions</strong> ‚Äî Typically 5-6% of the sale price</li>
        <li><strong>Recording fees</strong> ‚Äî For the deed and any lien releases</li>
        <li><strong>Prorated taxes</strong> ‚Äî Your share of property taxes through closing</li>
        <li><strong>HOA fees</strong> ‚Äî Prorated if applicable</li>
      </ul>

